Its use here in preference to ἁλυκόν or ἁλμυρόν is doubtless owing to its often being found in a figurative sense, e.g. ver. 14, ΡΞ. lxiv. 3, Sirao. iv. 6 καταρᾶσθαι ἐν πικρίᾳ ψυχῆς. It is descriptive of sea-water, like smum-us, our ‘brackish.' The Dead Sea however, to which St. James is p1·ol'›al.›ly alluding, was really bitter and had both salt and fresh springs on its shores. Other examples of bitter waters are Marah (Exod. XV. 23), ‘ the water that causeth the curse ’ (Numb. v. 18-27), Apoc. viii. 11.
